les on the same jet that took England to the Euros in Germany.The Labour leader sat in the same seat as England boss Gareth Southgate for the journey, part of a whirlwind tour of mainland Britain on the final day of the election campaign.03:24 PM BSTCabinet ‘definitely not’ resigned to election defeat, Sunak insistsRishi Sunak has insisted his Cabinet has “definitely not” given up on Thursday’s general election after Mel Stride appeared to admit defeat, Dominic Penna reports.The Work and Pensions Secretary said in an interview on Wednesday morning that Labour will likely win “the largest majority any party has ever achieved”.Asked on a visit to a primary school in Romsey, Hampshire whether he was the “only one” around the Cabinet table who had not “resigned themselves to defeat”, Mr Sunak said: “No, that’s definitely not right.“And look, you’ve seen the analysis that shows just 130,000 people switching their votes can make the difference in this election. Every vote matters.“Lots of people want to say it’s a foregone conclusion, but I don’t take that approach, right? Until the last moment I will be taking the same message to everyone I meet. If you want your taxes cut, your pensions protected and your borders secure, just get out there and vote Conservative.”Mr Stride suggested a Labour victory would surpass the majorities of 179 and 492 achieved in 1997 and 1931, with polls continuing to show the Tories trail Sir Keir Starmer’s party by around 20 percentage points.03:19 PM BSTPoll: Farage to win in ClactonNigel Farage will win in Clacton, the More In Common MRP poll has predicted.The Reform UK leader and Tory defector Lee Anderson were the only Reform candidates forecast to be returned to Parliament.The poll predicted that Mr Farage would win 36 per cent of the vote in the Essex seat, three points ahead of his Tory rival Giles Watling.Mr Anderson was predicted to win 49 per cent of the vote in Ashfield, well ahead of Labour on 20 per cent and the Conservatives on n